{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611010"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:06:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:06:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16195"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16195"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.45,0,0.15,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72419"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8886"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16195"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57889"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2333"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"10653"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21155"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72419"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman has just given birth to her first child via uncomplicated vaginal delivery at term in the hospital. Both mother and baby are well. The baby\u0027s Apgar scores were 9 and 9 at one and five minutes. The mother is keen to breastfeed and asks when she should start.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate time to initiate breastfeeding after delivery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Two to three hours after delivery","Within the first hour after delivery","One to two days after delivery","Three to six hours after delivery","One hour after delivery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe World Health Organization recommends initiating breastfeeding \u003Cstrong\u003Ewithin the first hour after delivery\u003C/strong\u003E. This timing takes advantage of the newborn\u0027s natural alertness and strong sucking reflex present in the first hour of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwo to three hours after delivery\u003C/strong\u003E misses the optimal window when babies are most alert and ready to feed. Delaying beyond the first hour can make it more challenging to establish successful breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne hour and Three to six hours after delivery\u003C/strong\u003E is too late and may result in a sleepy, less interested baby, making it more difficult to establish proper latching and feeding techniques.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne to two days after delivery\u003C/strong\u003E represents a significant and inappropriate delay. This would deny the baby important colostrum and could lead to the need for supplemental feeding, potentially interfering with the establishment of breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly initiation of breastfeeding has numerous benefits including: promoting mother-infant bonding, stimulating milk production, providing colostrum (which is rich in antibodies and nutrients), helping the uterus contract (reducing postpartum bleeding), and increasing the likelihood of successful long-term breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early skin-to-skin contact and initiation of breastfeeding within the first hour after birth promotes successful breastfeeding.","Early breastfeeding helps stimulate milk production, promotes bonding, and reduces postpartum bleeding.","Colostrum provides important immunological protection and nutrition for the newborn."],"references":["World Health Organization. Breastfeeding. WHO. Available from: https://www.who.int/health-topics/breastfeeding#tab=tab_1","Queensland Government. Expressing breast milk. Children\u0027s Health Queensland. Available from: https://www.childrens.health.qld.gov.au/health-a-to-z/breastfeeding/expressing-breast-milk","Roghair R. Breastfeeding: Benefits to Infant and Mother. Nutrients. 2024 Sep 26;16(19):3251. doi: 10.3390/nu16193251. PMID: 39408217; PMCID: PMC11478634.","Dieterich CM, Felice JP, O\u0027Sullivan E, Rasmussen KM. Breastfeeding and health outcomes for the mother-infant dyad. Pediatr Clin North Am. 2013 Feb;60(1):31-48. doi: 10.1016/j.pcl.2012.09.010. Epub 2012 Nov 3. PMID: 23178059; PMCID: PMC3508512."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57889"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16195"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57889"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T18:39:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T18:39:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8886"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72419"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"O